<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
One point in antimagic and a dark sword of nothingness (-lots, -lots) results in better antimagic than with a regular dark sword (+0, +0). <p>
This is immensely useful to noncaster archers! 
</p>
<hr size="3">
 <a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>:  Archers need a break, heh. <p>
Seriously, though, this is a risky practice.  With only one point in Anti-magic, you don't get trap detection/destruction, but can't use rods or staves for that purpose either. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a>: Not only that, but the (-lots,-lots) beneficial aspect is very well known. Not a bug. If the player doesn't research antimagic properly, or if the character doesn't invest enough skill points in antimagic in order to get the full benefits, that's their own fault. &lt;g&gt; 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./JulesBean">JulesBean</a>: What makes you so sure this is not a bug? It is certainly well known, but it's always seemed a bit broken to me. Weapons of Nothingness are presumably intended to be really bad things to wield to discourage you from wielding un-ID'ed weapons; I doubt they were intended as uber anti-magic weapons. 
</p>
<p>
As an aside, the whole magic bonus thing for unbelievers is riddled with inconsistency: a dark sword which is damaged by acid will suddenly radiate a stronger antimagic field.... 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: I know it's not a bug because I discussed it personally with the illustrious maintainer over a year ago. 
</p>
<p>
Simon: so Lord Dimwitt's strategy guide is wrong?? And I thought Lord Dimwitt had said elsewhere that strong antimagic with 1 point of antimagic was a standard strategy with his archers... 
</p>
<p>
If we had a clue of how antimagic REALLY works, which we don't and can't really measure, we'd know if this is a bug or not.   (and we'd actually know how effective antimagic is, which is important). 
</p>
<p>
In any case large negatives shouldn't give better antimagic than (+0, +0). Is it the case? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: You'll find that I indeed am not in that pseudonymous individual's fan club, falling over his every word. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Large negatives give better antimagic than (+0,+0). Absence of documentation is not a 'bug', it's an absence. I understand your frustration, Simon, but please have some patience. We can only do so much at a time. Do you want documentation, or ToME 3? <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/biggrin.png" alt=":D" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
Simon: I wand ToME 3 to be documented. Or else I'll be hearing "do you want documentation or ToME 4?" someday. (-; 
</p>
<p>
In the meantime, however, you might want to look <a class="external" href="./www.killerbunnies.org/angband/skill-220.html#antimagic"><img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">here</a> for a spoiler that explains exactly how dark swords work and why the negative values are important. Please search all the available sources before you get worked up, 'kay? Thanks. 
</p>
<p>
Simon: nice spoiler! Of course it doesn't mention if negative values count, and I wouldn't have guessed in a million years, but the formulas are extra nice. (-; 
</p>
